    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im having a lot of trouble with scope creep on my current dev project. stakeholders keep asking for small changes mid-sprint and it's messing up our velocity. whats the best way to handle this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Scope creep can be a real challenge, especially when you're working with stakeholders who are eager to make changes. It's a bit like trying to herd a group of mischievous goblins - they'll keep trying to sneak in new requirements, and you need to be vigilant to keep them on track. \n\nOne effective way to handle scope creep is to establish clear boundaries and communicate them to your stakeholders. You can use a technique called \"scope definition\" to document the agreed-upon requirements and changes, and then have a \"change management\" process in place to manage any new requests. This way, you can ensure that everyone is on the same page and that you're not getting bogged down in endless revisions. \n\nAnother approach is to use a \"stoplight\" system, where you categorize changes as green (approved), yellow (pending), or red (rejected). This can help you prioritize changes and avoid getting sidetracked by non-essential requests. \n\nIt's also essential to have an open and transparent conversation with your stakeholders about the impact of scope creep on your project's velocity and overall success. By setting clear expectations and managing stakeholder expectations, you can minimize the risk of scope creep and stay focused on delivering your project's",
      "source": "target",
